Tso’s Journey Pt. 8 The Final Trip (2 of 2)“Hello handsome,” her voice tantalized. “I brought what you wanted, now what do I get in return?”He smiled graciously, bowing as he took what she handed him and invited her in to sit down.“How much do they pay models for wearing whore couture these days?” Smooth words slipped from Vlad’s mouth.She hissed. “Well fuck. Why didn’t you tell me he was going to be here?”Tso lifted an eyebrow. “Have a seat, we need to talk.” Tsotinu explained what he saw with the ghost in Hollow. For vampires they both visibly paled. He prodded, “Tell me what you know.”They spilled the rumors they’d heard. All over Earth, paranormals were disappearing. Some in front of family members. Typically of high intelligence, mostly vampires and witches. Reportedly those that did return, and they were few, had no memory. They died, their body dissipating within hours of their reappearance. As if they restored as a shell of their former selves.Humans did not appear to see them. They assumed they came in on a different plane of existence because of being paras. What few witnesses there have been have mentioned a shimmering black wall. They’d heard of one or two other beings coming through, but they had been killed before they could do damage or died quickly; regardless of how they died, their bodies vanished the same way. “This has been occurring on and off for years, but in the last few weeks it appears to have escalated.” Elvira commented.“If this is part of your journey and there is anything we can do to help,” Vlad stood to leave, “all you have to do is ask.”Tso thanked them for their information as they left and made certain they had access to the local blood bank in return.He was weary with this news. It was time to go see his family.previous / next

We ordered our drinks and there was a lull in customers so Emmett managed to get a hold of the manager and ask about the open position. I took our drinks to an open table and waited while they chatted.“Mmm!” Emmett moaned as he took a slip of his coffee when he sat down, “I don’t know how you guys handle this cold!”“Bridgeport doesn’t get cold?”“Yeah, it does but definitely not this cold. Plus you get the heat from the grates that lead to the subway.” he says, taking another swig. “I really want to go one day…to see a real city would be so cool,” I say.“You live in a city, Em.” Emmett chuckled.“Ja, but I spent most of my life in a town the size of a postage stamp and then came here thinking this place was massive. But then I started looking up universities and then wound up searching Bridgeport…Aurora Skies is nothing in comparison.”“It is big, I’ll give you that.”☆  From the Beginning  ☆

David Pierre or as his friends and family members often call him, “Doc P,” is Haitian-American and hails from “Brick City” Newark, New Jersey. He attended the basketball powerhouse St. Patricks High School in Elizabeth, NJ (now “The Patrick School”). He then attended Cook College (School of Environmental and Biological Sciences) at Rutgers University where he credits the Equal Opportunity Fund (EOF) Program and the Office of Diversity for the Success and Sciences (ODASIS) for his academic and professional success. David then obtained a Masters of Science in Biological Sciences degree from the University of Medicine and Dentistry of New Jersey Graduate School of Biological Sciences (now Rowan). He subsequently matriculated into the Philadelphia College of Osteopathic Medicine (PCOM) in Philadelphia, PA to obtained his Doctorate of Osteopathic Medicine (DO). While in medical school he commissioned as an officer in the Delaware Air National Guard and proudly serves as a captain with intentions on becoming a flight surgeon. He did his residency training at Christiana Care Family Medicine Residency in Wilmington, DE the only full service Level 1 trauma center on the East corridor between Baltimore and Philadelphia. He served as  chief resident in his last year of post graduate training. During residency he completed a Training In Health Policy (TIPS) Fellowship with the American Osteopathic Association (AOA) and the New York Institute of Technology (NYIT). Following the completion of residency, he accepted a position as an Assistant Professor of Family and Community Medicine at the University of Missouri.
